@NODE Intro
@TITLE "DirShell Introduction"
Introduction-
        
        Dirshell is a simple yet useful tool that allows you to open a
system shell to any directory. This program came about because I was tired
of opening a shell and issuing a change of  directory to carry out simple 
tasks. This is not much of a problem when the path name is short, but if
the path name in very long it gets to be kind-of tedious.
 







@ENDNODE

@NODE What
@TITLE "What You need"
What you need-

        You need any Amiga with OS 2.0 or greater. You also need to have
the Amiga Dos command NewShell somewhere in your system path. Dirshell has
been tested on a 2000,3000,and 4000. 











@ENDNODE
@NODE HowTo
@TITLE "How to use DirShell"
How to use Dirshell-

        Dirshell is very easy to use. It can be ran only from workbench 
with or without icon arguments. Double-clicking on the Dirshell icon will
bring up a system file requester. Choose the directory you want the system
shell to open to and select OK. A shell will open with the directory you 
selected as the root directory. Only one shell can be open with the file
directory method.
        You can also select directories by passing icon arguments to 
Dirshell. Dirshell uses the standard Amiga Workbench startup message to 
receive all icon selected. You can select any type of icon. If a drawer
icon is selected then the shell opened will have the drawer directory as 
it's root. If any other type of icon is selected the root directory will be
the directory that icon resides in. Using the icon argument method allows 
you to open as many shell as you want, each to different directories. I have
found that using Dirshell with a ToolMaster type program can be very handy.
Just select all the icons you want, drop them on a AppIcon linked to 
Dirshell and you're off. 
         

@ENDNODE
@NODE Tool
@TITLE "ToolTypes"
ToolTypes-

        The two tooltypes 'WINDOW' and 'FROM' used with the system shell 
can be used with Dirshell. The file set by the FROM tooltype will be used 
with all shells open by Dirshell. The WINDOW tooltype will only be used if 
one shell is opened. When multiple shells are open at once Dirshell 
spreads them out on your Workbench screen. With the two tooltypes set as 
follows:
                      
                      WINDOW=CON:0/0/640/200/Myshell/CLOSE
                      FROM=s: startup-shell
                      
                              
A shell would be open 640 wide by 200 tall starting in the left-hand corner.
the file s: startup-shell would be used to define the shell. For more 
information on these tooltypes please see the user manual That came with
your OS 2.0 software.


@ENDNODE
